    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-07-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-07-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="261"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d261">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">195.1/482½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">29 July, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I asked Mr. Palmer<note n="87"
                        xml:id="d261fn1">A. Mitchell Palmer, judge, United States Court of
                        Claims.</note> to send me the enclosed,<note n="88" xml:id="d261fn2">Samples
                        of guarantees required of shippers to insure passage of goods through
                        British blockade.</note> as specimens of what is being sent to our shippers,
                    and I think that you ought to see them.</p>
                <p>The copy of the British note of the twenty-fourth [<hi rend="italic"
                        >twenty-third</hi>] of this month,<note n="89" xml:id="d261fn3">
                        <ref target="frus1915#pg_168">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1915, supp., p.
                        168</ref>.</note> which you sent me, has been received and read with the
                    closest attention. It seems to me, I must say, to make out a <pb facs="0371"
                        n="303" xml:id="pg_303"/> strong case. Pending the receipt of the
                    supplementary note, I should very much like an intimation of your first
                    impressions.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
